Case study report for Childhood body size

09 July 2022

Report for: Childhood body size (ukb-a-34)

This case study report includes the results for Childhood body size, generated automatically using Rmarkdown.

The report is split into 3(+1) parts:

  1. Mendelian randomization (MR) results for Childhood body size for all breast cancer outcomes (BCAC 2017 and 2020)
  2. Overview of potential mediators identified from MR-EvE data; their validation with two-step and multivariable MR (MVMR)
  3. Overview of potential mediators identified from literature-mined data; their validation with two-step, bidirectional, and MVMR
  4. Optional validation of results with female-only exposure data (if available)
  • Trait IDs in this report correspond to data available in OpenGWAS
  • BCAC 2017 outcomes names/IDs: Full sample (Breast cancer) ieu-a-1126, ER+ sample (ER+ Breast cancer)ieu-a-1127, ER- sample (ER- Breast cancer) ieu-a-1128
  • MR analyses in this report were performed using TwoSampleMR and MVMR packages
  • The two-sample MR estimates presented in this report were produced with inverse-variance weighted (IVW) or Wald ratio (for single SNP traits)

This report is a part of the publication Integrating Mendelian randomization and literature-mined evidence for breast cancer risk factors Vabistsevits et al 2022

1 Main analysis MR results

Childhood body size data details:

  • Source: UK Biobank
  • Sample size: > 450K
  • nSNPs: 144
  • Sample sex: mixed

Childhood body size was identified in MR-EvE search as having evidence of effect on breast cancer and validated with IVW MR method in BCAC 2017 and BCAC 2020 breast cancer outcomes:

The full MR results and sensitivity analysis are available in Supplementary Data 2 and 3.

2 MR-EvE-mined mediators

By querying MR-EvE data for Childhood body size we identified 38 potential mediators. This analysis was done only for BCAC 2017 outcomes (full / ER+ / ER-), and only those that were affected in the main MR analysis: full , ER+ , ER- sample(s)

3 Literature-mined mediators

We searched literature-mined relationships in EpiGraphDB for Childhood body size and breast cancer and used literature-overlap method to identify potential intermediates between the two. The identified intermediates are tested as potential mediaotrs in this section.

3.1 Summary

Childhood body size literature space contains:

  • 1255 unique triples of terms

  • 962 unique pairs of terms

3.2 Literature overlap Sankey plot

This is a Sankey plot of literature overlap between Childhood body size and breast cancer. See the subset versions and explore filters in a separate app: https://mvab.shinyapps.io/literature_overlap_sankey/

3.3 Matching literature terms to GWAS traits

Childhood body size and breast cancer literature space overlap identified:

  • 114 unique literature terms

  • 57 terms are available as GWAS traits in OpenGWAS (table below)

  • 40 (33 unique) traits have >=1 genome-wide significant SNPs (instruments for MR) (highlighted in the table)
